# EmX Backend Engineering Rules

## Core Philosophy

This project must follow production-grade backend engineering standards.

Prioritize:

- scalability
- maintainability
- observability
- strict typing
- clean architecture
- developer experience

DO NOT optimize for quick hacks.

---

# TypeScript Rules

- Always use strict mode
- Never use `any`
- Prefer `unknown` over `any`
- Use explicit return types for exported functions
- Use readonly where applicable
- Use discriminated unions when possible
- Prefer type safety over convenience

Required compiler settings:

- strict
- noUncheckedIndexedAccess
- exactOptionalPropertyTypes

---

# Architecture Rules

- Follow modular monorepo architecture
- Keep services isolated
- Shared logic belongs in packages/
- Never duplicate infrastructure code
- Never place business logic inside routes/controllers
- Use layered architecture:
  - interfaces
  - application
  - domain
  - infrastructure

---

# API Rules

- Use Fastify only
- Use async/await consistently
- Use schema validation
- All endpoints must:
  - validate input
  - handle errors properly
  - return typed responses

- Add `/health` endpoint to every service
- APIs must be versionable

---

# Validation Rules

- Use Zod for validation
- Validate:
  - env vars
  - request body
  - params
  - query
  - headers

Never trust incoming data.

---

# Environment Rules

- Never access process.env directly outside config package
- Use centralized env validation
- Fail fast if env validation fails

---

# Logging Rules

- Use structured logging
- Avoid console.log except bootstrap startup
- Logs must be machine-readable
- Prepare for future correlation IDs

---

# Docker Rules

- Use multi-stage Docker builds
- Keep images minimal
- Separate Dockerfile.dev and production Dockerfile
- Use docker-compose for local infrastructure

---

# Folder Structure Rules

Use:

- kebab-case for files
- PascalCase for types/classes
- camelCase for functions/variables

Avoid:

- giant files
- deeply nested logic
- mixed responsibilities

---

# Dependency Rules

Prefer:

- lightweight libraries
- composable utilities

Avoid:

- bloated abstractions
- unnecessary frameworks
- magic decorators

---

# Security Rules

- Never trust client input
- Prepare architecture for RBAC
- Sanitize inputs
- Avoid leaking internal errors
- Validate all configs

---

# Performance Rules

- Prepare for Redis caching
- Avoid unnecessary allocations
- Use async patterns properly
- Avoid blocking operations

---

# Monorepo Rules

- Shared configs belong in packages/
- Shared utilities belong in packages/
- Services belong in apps/
- Infrastructure belongs in infra/

---

# Code Quality Rules

Every package must support:

- build
- dev
- lint
- typecheck

All code must:

- pass ESLint
- pass TypeScript checks
- be formatted with Prettier

---

# Future Readiness

Architecture must be designed for:

- Supabase
- Redis
- BullMQ
- Pub/Sub
- OpenTelemetry
- Prometheus
- Grafana
- Kubernetes
- GitHub Actions
- CI/CD pipelines

Even if not implemented yet.
